\begin{abstract}
We investigate how the combination of non-equilibrium effects and material properties impacts on the
Casimir-Polder interaction between an atom and a surface. By addressing systems with temperature inhomogeneities and laser interactions, we show that non-monotonous energetic landscapes can be produced where barriers and minima appear. Our treatment provides a self-consistent quantum theoretical framework for investigating the properties of a class of non-equilibrium atom-surface interactions.
\end{abstract}

